# Creating a heatmap of feature correlation
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 10))
hide = np.tril(df.corr())
sns.heatmap(df.corr(), cmap="coolwarm", annot=True,
            fmt='.2f', annot_kws={'size':12},
            linewidths=0.5, square=True,)
            #mask= hide)
plt.show()

Heart Rate Correlations:

There is a significant correlation between Heart Rate and several features: Stress Level: Higher heart rates are associated with higher stress levels. Daily Steps: Heart rate varies significantly with the number of daily steps. Physical Activity Level: Increased physical activity levels are linked to higher heart rates. Stress Level Correlations:

Negative Correlations:

Quality of Sleep: There is a strong negative correlation between Stress Level and Quality of Sleep, indicating that higher stress levels are associated with poorer quality of sleep. Age: A negative correlation exists between Age and Stress Level, suggesting that older individuals tend to have lower stress levels.

Quality of Sleep Correlations:

Positive Correlation: Age: A positive correlation between Age and Quality of Sleep indicates that older individuals tend to report better quality of sleep. Negative Correlation: Stress Level: As mentioned, higher stress levels correlate with poorer quality of sleep. Age Correlations:

Negative Correlation: Stress Level: Older age is associated with lower stress levels. Positive Correlation: Quality of Sleep: Older Age is associated with better quality of sleep.

Correlations with Sleep Disorder:

There are slight correlations between the following predictors and the class variable Sleep Disorder: Age: Slight correlation with the likelihood of having a sleep disorder. Quality of Sleep: Slight correlation with sleep disorders.

There are strong positive correlations between High Blood Pressure and Low Blood Pressure, as well as between Daily Steps and Physical Activity Levels.

Additionally, strong negative correlations were observed between Stress Level and both Sleep Duration and Quality of Sleep. Similarly, there is a moderate negative correlation between Heart Rate and both Sleep Duration and Quality of Sleep.

Moderate positive correlations were found between Age and both High Blood Pressure, Low Blood Pressure, and Occupation_Nurse. Conversely, moderate negative correlations were observed between Age and Gender_Male, Occupation_Doctor, and BMI Category_Overweight.

Moreover, moderate positive correlations were noted between Occupation_Nurse and both High Blood Pressure and Low Blood Pressure, as well as between BMI Category_Overweight and both High Blood Pressure and Low Blood Pressure. Furthermore, there is a moderate positive correlation between Heart Rate and BMI Category_Obese.

In [42]:
#import libraries
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest
from sklearn.feature_selection import mutual_info_classif

selector = SelectKBest(score_func=mutual_info_classif, k='all') # f_classif to get feature scores
selector.fit(X, y) # fitting with selector

f_scores = selector.scores_ # get feature scores
f_names = X.columns # get feature names

f_scores_df = pd.DataFrame({'Feature': f_names, 'Score': f_scores})# dataframe to store feature name and score
f_scores_df = f_scores_df.sort_values(by='Score', ascending=False) # sort the feature score 

f_scores_df # display the feature with scores

## Select the top features based on score
select = SelectKBest(score_func=mutual_info_classif, k=12)  # Select top features

# Load multipple classification models 
# Loop over the models and review results

models = []
models.append(('LR', LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear', multi_class='ovr')))
models.append(('LDA', LinearDiscriminantAnalysis()))
models.append(('KNN', KNeighborsClassifier()))
models.append(('CART', DecisionTreeClassifier()))
models.append(('NB', GaussianNB()))
models.append(('SVM', SVC(gamma='auto')))
models.append(('RF',RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs=-1)))
models.append(('CB',CatBoostClassifier(verbose = False)))
models.append (('GB', GradientBoostingClassifier()))


## Evaluate each model in turn
results = [] # print the accuracy score
names = []   # print the model name

for name, model in models: # loop over the models to get the accuracy score of both train and test
    fit = model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    train_predict = model.predict(X_train)
    test_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    accuracy_train = accuracy_score(y_train,train_predict)
    accuracy_test = accuracy_score(y_test,test_predict)
    
    results.append({
        'Model': name,
        'Score': [accuracy_train, accuracy_test]
    })
    
result_df = pd.DataFrame(results) # data frame of the results
result_df['Score'] = result_df['Score'].apply(lambda x: ['{:.2f}'.format(score) for score in x]) # round to 2 decimals
result_df = result_df.set_index('Score') # set index as score
result_df = result_df.sort_values(by='Score', ascending=False)

## K-fold cross validation on training set

results = []

for name, model in models:
    kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, random_state=1, shuffle=True)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')
    results.append((name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std()))

# Sort results by mean accuracy in descending order
results.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)

# Print the sorted results
for name, mean_accuracy, std_dev in results:
    print(f"{name}: {mean_accuracy*100:.2f}% ({std_dev:.3f})")
    print()

# Retrain with gradient booster classifier

gbc = GradientBoostingClassifier(
    learning_rate=0.01,       # Learning rate
    max_depth=3,              # Maximum depth of the individual estimators
    min_samples_leaf=4,       # Minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node
    min_samples_split=2,      # Minimum number of samples required to split an internal node
    n_estimators=300,         # Number of boosting stages
    subsample=0.8             # Fraction of samples used for fitting the individual base learners
)

# Fit the model on the training data
gbc.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict on the test data

ACCURACY

</font>

Accuracy is a measure of the overall performance of a classification model. It is calculated as the ratio of correctly predicted instances (sum of true positives and true negatives) to the total number of instances evaluated.

Accuracy: 0.9467 means that the model correctly predicted 94.67% of the samples in the test dataset.

CONFUSION MATRIX

</font>

A confusion matrix is a table that summarizes the performance of a classification model. It compares the actual target values with the values predicted by the model.

Class 1 (None):

True Negatives (TN): 42 False Positives (FP): 0 False Negatives (FN): 1 (predicted as Insomnia, but actually Sleep Apnea) True Positives (TP): 16

Class 2 (Sleep Apnea):

True Negatives (TN): 42 (sum of the first column) False Positives (FP): 1 (predicted as None, but actually Sleep Apnea) False Negatives (FN): 1 (predicted as Insomnia, but actually Sleep Apnea) True Positives (TP): 16

Class 3 (Insomnia):

True Negatives (TN): 42 (sum of the first column) False Positives (FP): 2 (predicted as None, but actually Insomnia) False Negatives (FN): 0 True Positives (TP): 13

CLASSIFICATION REPORT

</font>

A classification report provides a detailed evaluation of the model's performance on each class in the dataset. It includes several metrics:

  • Precision, Recall, F1-score, Support:

    • Class 1 (None):

      • Precision: 0.93 (93% of instances predicted as None were actually None)
      • Recall: 1.00 (100% of actual None instances were correctly predicted as None)
      • F1-score: 0.97 (balanced measure of precision and recall)
      • Support: 42 (number of instances in the test dataset)

    • Class 2 (Sleep Apnea):

      • Precision: 1.00 (100% precision indicates no false positives for this class)
      • Recall: 0.89 (89% of actual Sleep Apnea instances were correctly predicted)
      • F1-score: 0.94 (weighted average of precision and recall)
      • Support: 18

    • Class 3 (Insomnia):

      • Precision: 0.93 (93% precision indicates few false positives for this class)
      • Recall: 0.87 (87% of actual Insomnia instances were correctly predicted)
      • F1-score: 0.90 (a measure of a test's accuracy)
      • Support: 15

SUMMARY¶

The dataset was obtained from Kaggle, a popular platform for datasets and data science competitions.

In the data preprocessing phase, I transformed features into numeric formats, categorized values where necessary, and introduced new features to enhance model performance.

Following preprocessing, I trained nine different machine learning models and selected four for further evaluation. Among them, three models demonstrated similar accuracy and performance metrics. After careful consideration, I chose the random forest model for its robust performance.

I conducted cross-validation to rigorously assess the random forest model's performance. Delving into the inner workings of the algorithm, I analyzed feature importance and fine-tuned hyperparameters to optimize model performance.

Lastly, I evaluated the random forest model using the confusion matrix, precision, recall, and F-score metrics. These evaluations provided comprehensive insights into the model's effectiveness in predicting Sleep Disorders.

Key factors identified as significantly influencing Sleep Disorders include: 'Age', 'Sleep Duration', 'Quality of Sleep', 'Physical Activity Level', 'Stress Level', 'Heart Rate', 'Daily Steps', 'BloodPressure_High', 'BloodPressure_Low', 'Occupation_Nurse', 'Occupation_Salesperson', and 'BMI Category_Overweight'.

This analysis not only highlights the predictive capabilities of the random forest model but also underscores the importance of these factors in understanding and potentially mitigating Sleep Disorders.
